types.name: SettingInputValue
types.description:
Value for a setting. The rules for a setting value are as follows:

* Each entry in SettingValue corresponds to a SettingType.

* The name should reflect the SettingType (e.g., if the SettingType
  is "String", then the field should be called "stringValue")

* Each field is nullable.

* Only the field with the appropriate value should be non-null.

* The field with the appropriate value should always be non-null.

Essentially, this is an implicit union. We don't use union semantics
since unions can't be used in input types (see
https://github.com/graphql/graphql-spec/issues/488), and we want loading and
setting Settings to be symmetric.

types.name: InteractionV3Type
types.description:
The collection of action types for the v3 interactions table.

Be VERY CAREFUL about extending the action types here. In general, we want
to have a very limited number of action types. If you need more information
about the context of an action, consider using Element, ElementAction, or
the Attributes table.

PLEASE KEEP IN SYNC with //schemas/constants/interaction_type.go.

enumValues.name: Click
enumValues.description:
Click covers all outbound clicks, i.e. anything that takes you outside of
neeva.

enumValues.name: View
enumValues.description:
View represents a view, according to the definition we've set (e.g. may or
may not be delayed).

enumValues.name: InternalClick
enumValues.description:
InternalClick represents a non-outbound click, and involves
the user interacting with some semantically meaningful part of a widget that
does not cause the user to leave the search context. Usually this is
something like navigating a carousel, showing more information, or seeing a
preview. Excludes MetaClicks.

enumValues.name: MetaClick
enumValues.description:
MetaClick represents a non-outbound click, and involves the
user interacting with a search element that changes the users relationship
to that element. This can be hide, follow, add to space, etc. Unlike an
InternalClick, a MetaClick does not involve the user interacting with the
element in a way that provides more information to the user.

enumValues.name: Refinement
enumValues.description:
Refinement is an interaction that initiates another, related search context,
i.e. by applying a corpus filter or opening a related search.

types.name: InteractionV3Category
types.description:
InteractionV3Category specifies the type of the item in the log tree hierarchy.
The log tree can have have N number of entries, but these are the ones
that have IDs associated.

PLEASE KEEP IN SYNC with //schemas/constants/category.go

enumValues.name: page
enumValues.description: Represents a page, such as a search results page or a space page.

enumValues.name: group
enumValues.description:
Represents a group of results or containers. This is synonymous with "result
group".

enumValues.name: container
enumValues.description: Represents a container of results, such as a news list or video carousel.

enumValues.name: result
enumValues.description:
Represents a single result. The result can be simple (a web link) or complex
(a rich entity), but this is the terminal category to which an action can
belong.

types.name: __Type
types.description:
The fundamental unit of any GraphQL Schema is the type. There are many kinds of types in GraphQL as represented by the `__TypeKind` enum.

Depending on the kind of a type, certain fields describe information about that type. Scalar types provide no information beyond a name, description and optional `specifiedByUrl`, while Enum types provide their values. Object and Interface types provide the fields they describe. Abstract types, Union and Interface, provide the Object types possible at runtime. List and NonNull types compose other types.

enumValues.name: INTERFACE
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an interface. `fields`, `interfaces`, and `possibleTypes` are valid fields.

enumValues.name: UNION
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a union. `possibleTypes` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: ENUM
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an enum. `enumValues` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: INPUT_OBJECT
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an input object. `inputFields` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: LIST
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a list. `ofType` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: NON_NULL
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a non-null. `ofType` is a valid field.

types.description: Object and Interface types are described by a list of Fields, each of which has a name, potentially a list of arguments, and a return type.

types.name: __Directive

A Directive provides a way to describe alternate runtime execution and type validation behavior in a GraphQL document.

In some cases, you need to provide options to alter GraphQL's execution behavior in ways field arguments will not suffice, such as conditionally including or skipping a field. Directives provide this by describing additional information to the executor.
